    <!-- 3. Four metrics -->
    <h3>Four metrics on the same set</h3>
    <p>The same set of points can carry different metrics. Each metric defines a different notion of distance, different open balls, and different convergent sequences. The set does not change. The structure does.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Four metrics on pairs of real numbers

; 1. Euclidean: sqrt(dx^2 + dy^2)
(define (d-euclidean p q)
  (let ((dx (- (car p) (car q)))
        (dy (- (cadr p) (cadr q))))
    (sqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))

; 2. Taxicab (Manhattan): |dx| + |dy|
(define (d-taxicab p q)
  (+ (abs (- (car p) (car q)))
     (abs (- (cadr p) (cadr q)))))

; 3. Chebyshev (L-infinity): max(|dx|, |dy|)
(define (d-chebyshev p q)
  (max (abs (- (car p) (car q)))
       (abs (- (cadr p) (cadr q)))))

; 4. Discrete: 0 if same, 1 otherwise
(define (d-discrete p q)
  (if (equal? p q) 0 1))

(define a (list 0 0))
(define b (list 3 4))

(display "Euclidean:  ") (display (d-euclidean a b)) (newline)
(display "Taxicab:    ") (display (d-taxicab a b)) (newline)
(display "Chebyshev:  ") (display (d-chebyshev a b)) (newline)
(display "Discrete:   ") (display (d-discrete a b))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def d_euclidean(p, q):
    return math.sqrt(sum((a-b)**2 for a,b in zip(p,q)))

def d_taxicab(p, q):
    return sum(abs(a-b) for a,b in zip(p,q))

def d_chebyshev(p, q):
    return max(abs(a-b) for a,b in zip(p,q))

def d_discrete(p, q):
    return 0 if p == q else 1

a, b = (0, 0), (3, 4)
print(f"Euclidean:  {d_euclidean(a, b)}")
print(f"Taxicab:    {d_taxicab(a, b)}")
print(f"Chebyshev:  {d_chebyshev(a, b)}")
print(f"Discrete:   {d_discrete(a, b)}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Hausdorff distance -->
    <h3>Hausdorff distance</h3>
    <p>The <strong>Hausdorff distance</strong> measures how far apart two <em>sets</em> are. It is the greatest distance any point in one set has to travel to reach the other set. If H(A, B) = 0, the closures of A and B are equal. Hausdorff distance turns the collection of compact subsets of a metric space into a metric space itself.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Hausdorff distance between two finite point sets
; H(A,B) = max(sup_a inf_b d(a,b), sup_b inf_a d(a,b))

(define (d-euclidean p q)
  (let ((dx (- (car p) (car q)))
        (dy (- (cadr p) (cadr q))))
    (sqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))

(define (min-dist point set)
  (apply min (map (lambda (q) (d-euclidean point q)) set)))

(define (directed-hausdorff A B)
  (apply max (map (lambda (a) (min-dist a B)) A)))

(define (hausdorff A B)
  (max (directed-hausdorff A B)
       (directed-hausdorff B A)))

; Two small sets
(define set-A (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1)))
(define set-B (list (list 2 0) (list 3 0) (list 2 1)))

(display "H(A, B) = ") (display (hausdorff set-A set-B))
; Furthest any point in A must travel to reach B
`} />


    <!-- 5. Metric space as enriched category -->
    <h3>Metric space as enriched category</h3>
    <p>A metric space is a category enriched over ([0, &infin;], &ge;, +). Objects are points. The hom-value from x to y is d(x, y). Identity says d(x, x) = 0. Composition says d(x, z) &le; d(x, y) + d(y, z), which is exactly the triangle inequality. Lawvere noticed this in 1973: a metric space is what you get when you replace "arrows exist or not" (Bool-enriched) with "arrows have a cost" ([0, &infin;]-enriched).</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Metric space as enriched category:
; - Objects: points
; - hom(x,y) = d(x,y) in [0, inf]
; - Identity: d(x,x) = 0
; - Composition: d(x,z) <= d(x,y) + d(y,z)
;
; Compare with a Bool-enriched category (preorder):
; - hom(x,y) = #t or #f
; - Identity: hom(x,x) = #t
; - Composition: hom(x,y) AND hom(y,z) => hom(x,z)
;
; Replacing Bool with [0,inf] and AND with +
; and TRUE with 0, turns a preorder into a metric space.

(define (d p q)
  (let ((dx (- (car p) (car q)))
        (dy (- (cadr p) (cadr q))))
    (sqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))))

(define x (list 0 0))
(define y (list 1 1))
(define z (list 3 0))

; Identity law: d(x,x) = 0
(display "d(x,x) = ") (display (d x x)) (newline)

; Triangle inequality = composition law
(display "d(x,z) = ") (display (d x z)) (newline)
(display "d(x,y) + d(y,z) = ")
(display (+ (d x y) (d y z))) (newline)
(display "composition holds? ")
(display (<= (d x z) (+ (d x y) (d y z))))
`} />


